1879.

Broadway, west side, north across Rector Street, showing prominently Trinity Church and Churchyard occupying the frontage from Rector to Thames Streets. Beyond is the Western Union Building with clock tower atop.

About 1885

Gift of Urbrock Collection

Broadway, between Rector and Thames Street, East Side and at the head of Wall Street, showing Trinity Church, P. E. It was granted a Royal Charter in 1697.
Ref: King's Handbook to New York, 1892
Pp 341-342

About 1890

Detroit Photograph Co.
Copyright.

Broadway, at the S. W. corner of Rector Street. Shown is the building in which the financier Russell Sage was the object of a bomb explosion that injured an innocent bystander. This structure was replaced in 1897 by the 21 story Empire Building. On the right is a view westward on Rector Street to Trinity Place. The Rector Street station of the Sixth Avenue Elevated Line appears there. At the margin is a portion of Trinity Churchyard.

About 1895

Trinity Church, P.E. located on Broadway, between Rector and Thames Streets, at the head of Wall Street.

Brown Bros.

Broadway between Rector and Thames Street, Wall Street, showing the Equitable Building and The Trinity Church yard.

1912

General View Lower Manhattan, West Side: Looking north across the area west of Broadway from Rector Street. On the extreme left is West Street with the tall West Street Building (at Albany Street) thereon. On the right is the Trinity Building and the towers of the Singer and Woolworth Buildings.

Views 2 and 3 show the Hudson terminal buildings and the Woolworth Building.

George L. Balgue

73-69 Broadway, at the S.W. corner of Rector Street, showing the 21-story Empire Building. The street on the right is Rector Street, of which this structure forms the south side while Trinity Grave Yard forms the other. On Trinity Place is a station of the Sixth Ave. Elevated Line.

About 1915.

Gift of E.M. Jenks.
Underhill.

73 to 51 Broadway (left), west side, south from and including Rector Street, to a point slightly south of Exchange Alley, showing the 21-story Empire Building (Nos. 73-69), the 21-story American Railway Express Co. Building (Nos. 65-63), and the lower floors of the 32-story Adams Building (Nos. 61-57). Also shown (right) is Rector Street, south side, west from Broadway, to Trinity Place, showing that side of the Empire Building.

August 7, 1929.

P. L. Sperr.
